vectorData.altText: 3. In a lower motor neuron lesion, muscle tone is ______________.

That's right!  Normal muscle tone will be expected in LMN lesion. In flaccid paralysis, the examiner does not experience abnormal resistance when passively moving the patientâ€™s limb. (You will learn more about this later!)
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

IPSILATERAL WEAKNESS: the target muscle becomes weak or, if ALL of its motor neurons are damaged, paralysed.  Usually individual muscles are affected rather than groups of muscles.
HYPOREFLEXIA: reflex activity is diminished or abolished because the LMN forms the efferent part of the reflex arc.
FLACCID PARALYSIS: normal (not â†“) muscle tone in the target muscles.
ATROPHY: loss of trophic substances from the nerve results in death of muscle fibres and a marked â†“ muscle mass over time. 
FASCICULATIONS: visible twitching of muscle fibers occurs in the early stage of wasting.
